    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The formation of high-mass stars remains a puzzle in astrophysics. At the heart of the problem is the characterization of the initial conditions, a phase that is short-lived and challenging to observe. Infrared-dark clouds (IRDCs) are molecular cloud complexes in which these phases exist, and this proposal aims to examine the kinematics and chemical evolution of cores (0.1pc) embedded within a filamentary IRDC. We select a well-studied region in G11.11-0.12, for which we have Herschel and N2H+(1-0) maps from the Plateau de Bure. We propose to study this region in the N2D+(2-1) and DNC(2-1) transitions to address following questions: (1) how does the deuterium fraction vary with evolutionary stage in the deeply embedded envrions of IRDCs? (2) what is the thermal structure and history of cores? (3) what is the kinematic profile of cores? The multiple tracers observed in this program will provide the physical and kinematic profile over 3 dex in density.  Employing a chemical model using a deuterium chemistry network, we can then constrain the temperature profile and place the current empirical evolutionary trends in the literature on firm theoretical footing.</prp:abstract>
